<doc id="532542" wikidata="Q814361" url="?curid=532542" title="Companion matrix">
<text>In linear algebra, the Frobenius companion matrix of the monic polynomial
formula_1
is the square matrix defined as

formula_2

Some authors use the transpose of this matrix, formula_3, which is more convenient for some purposes such as linear recurrence relations (see below).

formula_4 is defined from the coefficients of formula_5, while the characteristic polynomial as well as the minimal polynomial of formula_4 are equal to formula_7. In this sense, the matrix formula_4 and the polynomial formula_5 are &quot;companions&quot;.

==Similarity to companion matrix==
Any matrix with entries in a field has characteristic polynomial formula_10, which in turn has companion matrix formula_4. These matrices are related as follows.

The following statements are equivalent:
* &quot;A&quot; is similar over &quot;F&quot; to formula_4, i.e. &quot;A&quot; can be conjugated to its companion matrix by matrices in GL&quot;n&quot;(&quot;F&quot;);
* the characteristic polynomial formula_13 coincides with the minimal polynomial of &quot;A&quot; , i.e. the minimal polynomial has degree &quot;n&quot;;
* the linear mapping formula_14 makes formula_15 a cyclic formula_16-module, having a basis of the form formula_17; or equivalently formula_18 as formula_16-modules.

If the above hold, one says that &quot;A&quot; is &quot;non-derogatory&quot;.

Not every square matrix is similar to a companion matrix, but every square matrix is similar to a block diagonal matrix made of companion matrices. If we also demand that the polynomial of each diagonal block divides the next one, they are uniquely determined by &quot;A&quot;, and this gives the rational canonical form of &quot;A&quot;. 

==Diagonalizability==
The roots of the characteristic polynomial formula_5 are the eigenvalues of formula_4. If there are &quot;n&quot; distinct eigenvalues formula_22, then formula_4 is diagonalizable as formula_24, where &quot;D&quot; is the diagonal matrix and &quot;V&quot; is the Vandermonde matrix corresponding to the &#x27;s: 
formula_25
Indeed, a reasonably hard computation shows that the transpose formula_3 has eigenvectors formula_27 with formula_28, which follows from formula_29. Thus, its diagonalizing change of basis matrix is formula_30, meaning formula_31, and taking the transpose of both sides gives formula_24.

We can read the eigenvectors of formula_4 with formula_34 from the equation formula_24: they are the column vectors of the inverse Vandermonde matrix formula_36. This matrix is known explicitly, giving the eignevectors formula_37, with coordinates equal to the coefficients of the Lagrange polynomials
formula_38
Alternatively, the scaled eigenvectors formula_39 have simpler coefficients.

If formula_13 has multiple roots, then formula_4 is not diagonalizable. Rather, the Jordan canonical form of formula_4 contains one Jordan block for each distinct root; if the multiplicity of the root is &quot;m&quot;, then the block is an &quot;m&quot; × &quot;m&quot; matrix with formula_43 on the diagonal and 1 in the entries just above the diagonal. in this case, &quot;V&quot; becomes a confluent Vandermonde matrix.

